HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 984
By Faison
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend Representative Johnny
Garrett for his service as a member of the House
of Representatives.
WHEREAS, it is most appropriate that the members of this General Assembly should
honor those fellow legislators who have performed their duties with the utmost integrity and
whose efforts during their time in office have been dedicated to providing thoughtful and
exemplary service to their districts and to this great State; and
WHEREAS, Representative Johnny Garrett of Goodlettsville is one such distinguished
public servant, who has served both his constituency and this legislative body with honor and
ability; and
WHEREAS, during his tenure on Capitol Hill, Representative Garrett has been a highly
influential figure in the political, social, and civic life of Sumner County, and he has served his
constituents in numerous capacities, always working diligently at his elected duties and
expending the necessary effort to understand the opposing sides of complex issues; and
WHEREAS, Representative Johnny Garrett has distinguished himself as a public-
spirited citizen of the highest order and as an exceptional asset to the good people of the 45th
House District, whom he has served as a member of the 111th, 112th, 113th, and 114th General
Assemblies; and
WHEREAS, throughout his service, Representative Garrett has been prominent as a
dedicated and well-informed legislator who always votes his conscience; and
WHEREAS, an active and dynamic participant in the legislative process during his time
in the General Assembly, Representative Johnny Garrett has rendered sterling service as a
member of the Calendar & Rules Committee, the Finance, Ways and Means Committee, the
Judiciary Committee, the Appropriations and Oversight Subcommittee, the Civil Justice
HJR0984
012808
- 1 -

Subcommittee, and the Joint Ways and Means Committee and as Majority Whip for the 111th,
112th, 113th, and 114th General Assemblies; and
WHEREAS, Representative Garrett earned a Bachelor of Science degree in Business
Administration from the University of Tennessee, Knoxville, and a Doctor of Law degree from
the Nashville School of Law and has enjoyed a fruitful career as an attorney; and
WHEREAS, an active part of his community, he has served as president of
Goodlettsville Little League Baseball, co-founder of the 100 Club of Sumner County, Inc., and
as a board member of the Vol State Community College Foundation and Forward Sumner
Economic Partnership; and
WHEREAS, he is also a member of the Hendersonville Rotary Club, the Republican
Party of Sumner County, the Hendersonville Chamber of Commerce, the Goodlettsville
Chamber of Commerce, the Tennessee Bar Association, and the Sumner County Bar
Association; and
WHEREAS, his many professional accomplishments aside, Representative Garrett is
most thankful for the love and support of his wife and their three children; and
WHEREAS, throughout his outstanding career as a public servant, Johnny Garrett has
worked tirelessly on behalf of his constituents, bringing to his office an honorable bearing and
the traditional values of hard work and common sense; and
WHEREAS, Representative Johnny Garrett is wholly committed to the noble precepts of
public service that have earned Tennessee recognition as the Volunteer State, and he should
be specially recognized for his exemplary tenure in the General Assembly; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we hereby honor Representative Johnny Garrett for his meritorious service
to Tennessee as a member of the House of Representatives, commend him for his countless
- 2 - 012808

contributions and many good works in service of his constituents in the 45th House District, and
extend to him our best wishes for much continued success and happiness.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
